# Day 50 - Validate Binary Search Tree & Search in a Binary Search Tree

## Problems

### 1. LeetCode 98 - Validate Binary Search Tree

**Topic:** Binary Search Tree (BST), Depth-First Search (DFS), Recursion

### Approach

Traverse the tree recursively while maintaining a valid range for each node. Every node must have a value greater than the lower bound and less than the upper bound. Update these bounds as you move down the tree to ensure the BST property is maintained throughout the entire tree.

### What I Learned

- Validating a BST using value boundaries
- Passing constraints through recursive calls
- Why ancestor nodes influence the validity of descendants
- Applying DFS to verify BST properties

### Difficulty Faced

Initially, I thought checking only the immediate parent-child relationship would be enough. I learned that every node must satisfy the constraints imposed by all of its ancestor nodes.

### Complexity

- **Time Complexity:** O(n)
- **Space Complexity:** O(h)

---

### 2. LeetCode 700 - Search in a Binary Search Tree

**Topic:** Binary Search Tree (BST), Recursion

### Approach

Starting from the root, compare the target value with the current node. Move left if the value is smaller or right if it is larger. Continue recursively until the value is found or the tree ends.

### What I Learned

- Efficient searching using BST properties
- Eliminating half of the search space at each step
- Recursive traversal based on node values
- Difference between Binary Trees and Binary Search Trees

### Difficulty Faced

Remembering that the ordering property of a BST allows entire subtrees to be skipped, making searching much more efficient than in a normal binary tree.

### Complexity

- **Time Complexity:** O(h)
- **Space Complexity:** O(h)

